explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER — This is a macro invoked on the module_prop parameter at the top of the function. Its expansion could contain code that assigns to the module_prop parameter (or otherwise mutates the parameter variable) so the macro definition must be inspected to ensure it does not reassign the parameter (which would violate the MISRA rule).

OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET — This macro is used to obtain record and module pointers; macros can expand to code that references or assigns local parameters. Inspecting its definition verifies it does not reassign module_prop or otherwise mutate the function parameter variable.

OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl — This callee is passed module_prop. Although called functions cannot directly change the caller’s local parameter variable unless given its address, verify its prototype/implementation to ensure it is not called with &module_prop somewhere (it is not in this function) and that there are no macro indirections that pass module_prop by address. Also verify it does not rely on any macro that might mutate the caller’s parameter.

OS_ObjectIdGetById — This function is called before any use of module_prop; inspect its implementation/signature and any macros it uses to ensure it does not expand into code that could reassign module_prop (for example via unusual macros or global side-effects). This is defensive: some platforms use macros that interact with local variables.

OS_ObjectIdRelease — Similar to OS_ObjectIdGetById: check its implementation/macros for any code that could affect the module_prop parameter variable (e.g. via macros or code generation patterns).

memset — Standard library call that writes to the object pointed to by module_prop (memset(module_prop,...)). Include it to confirm it only modifies the object pointed-to (allowed by MISRA) and does not reassign the module_prop parameter itself.

strncpy — Standard library call used to write into fields of *module_prop. Include to confirm it modifies the pointee (allowed) and not the pointer variable.

OS_module_prop_t — The type definition of the parameter. Inspecting the typedef/struct is needed to ensure there is no trick (e.g. typedef to pointer-to-pointer) that would change the meaning of the parameter and whether assignments or operations might actually reassign the parameter value.

OS_common_record_t and OS_module_internal_record_t — These types are used to obtain data copied into fields of *module_prop. Inspect their definitions to ensure the field accesses and the macros used to get them do not involve any unusual macro expansions that could assign to module_prop itself.

Rationale: The MISRA rule in question prohibits assigning to a function parameter variable. The above symbols are the macros, functions, and type definitions that appear in or could expand into code that might reassign or otherwise modify the parameter variable module_prop. Reviewing these symbols (macro expansions and function prototypes/implementations) is sufficient to determine whether module_prop (the pointer variable) is ever assigned to in OS_ModuleInfo; direct writes to *module_prop (via memset/strncpy/OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl) are allowed and should be distinguished from assignments to module_prop itself.
